\begin_layout Standard
Pacman is the Arch Linux
\series bold
 pac
\series default
kage
\series bold
man
\series default
ager.
 This underpins Pamac and Octopi but doesn't have a graphical interface.
 Instead, it is used by typing commands on the terminal.
 The commands allow you to install, upgrade, configure, and remove software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Synchronising with the Manjaro repositories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As new packages are added to the repositories you will need to regularly
 synchronise the package lists.
 This is normally taken care of automatically on a regular basis by the
 software managers, but to perform this manually type the following into
 the terminal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Sy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This will only download the package lists if there has been a change.
 Occasionally you may want to force the package lists to be downloaded.
 To do this, type:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Updating software
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pacman will allow you to perform an update of software already installed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Su
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's a good idea to check whether the package lists are up-to-date at the
 same time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can also force a package list synchronisation before performing an update:
