\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Syyu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Searching for software
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finding a package by name is really straightforward.
 For example, to search for a text editor called Leafpad:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Ss leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Installing software
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Installing a package is equally straightforward.
 For example, to install Leafpad:
\begin_inset Flex Marginnote
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Many software applications depend on other software packages.
 Thankfully, pacman will automatically detect and install these!
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -S leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Removing software
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To remove a software package you need to know its name, but the command
 is straightforward.
 To remove Leafpad:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -R leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's also possible to remove a package and any dependencies it required
 when it was installed.
 Assuming those other packages are not being used by another piece of software,
 they will become
\series bold
 orphan
\series default
 packages.
 These serve no function other than taking up space! To remove a software
 package with its dependencies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Rs leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A package may also create configuration files.
 Normally these are left in place so your configuration is not lost, and
 can be reused if you install the package again.
 However, if you want to remove these configuration files too, the command
 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Rns leafpad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If at a later date you want to remove all orphan packages and configuration
 files for packages that you removed some time ago, the following command
 will do it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\family typewriter
sudo pacman -Rns $(pacman -Qtdq)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be warned, though: this is an advanced command!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Other pacman commands
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's a good idea to become familiar with the pacman commands.
 It can be a very useful tool in case the other software managers refuse
 to complete an installation, for example if an installation process is
 interrupted.
 The pacman man
